[0.001, "o", "\r\u001b[2d; a more efficient layout for servers that handle many sessions.\r\u001b[3d;\u001b[K\u001b[4d NOTE 1: PHP will not create this directory structure automatically.\r\u001b[5d;         You can use the script in the ext/session dir for that purpose.\r\u001b[6d; NOTE 2: See the section on garbage collection below if you choose to\u001b[7;3H        use subdirectories for session storage\u001b[8;3H\u001b[K\r\u001b[9d; The file storage module creates files using mode 600 by default.\r\u001b[10d; You can change that by using\u001b[11;3H\u001b[K\u001b[12d    session.save_path = \"N;MODE;/path\"\u001b[13;3H\u001b[K\u001b[14d\b"]
[0.001, "o", " where MODE is the octal representation of the mode. Note that this\r\u001b[15d; does not overwrite the process's umask.\u001b[16;3Hhttps://php.net/session.save-path\u001b[K\r\u001b[17d;session.save_path = \"/tmp\"\u001b[K\r\u001b[18d\u001b[K\u001b[19d; Whether to use strict session mode.\u001b[20;3HStrict session mode does not accept an uninitialized session ID, and\r\u001b[21d; regenerates the session ID if the browser sends an uninitialized session ID.\r\u001b[22d; Strict mode protects applications from session fixation via a session adoption\r\u001b[23d; vulnerability. It is disabled by default for maximum compatibility, but\u001b[24;3Henabling it is encouraged.\r\u001b[25d; https://wiki.php.net/rfc/strict_sessions\r\u001b[26dsession.use_strict_mode = 0\r\u001b[27d\u001b[K\u001b[28d; Whether to use cookies.\u001b[K\r\u001b[29d; https://php.net/session.use-cookies\r\u001b[30dsession.use_cookies = 1\r\u001b[31d\u001b[K\u001b[32;19Hsession.cookie-s"]
[0.000, "o", "ecure\r\u001b[33d;\u001b[30m\u001b[43msession.cookie_\u001b[39;49m\u001b[m\u000fsecure =\u001b[35;3Hhttps://php.net/session.cookie-partitioned\u001b[K\r\u001b[36d;session.cookie_partitioned = 0\r\u001b[37d\u001b[K\u001b[38d; This option forces PHP to fetch and use a cookie for storing and maintaining\r\u001b[39d; the session id. We encourage this operation as it's very helpful in combating\u001b[40;3Hsession hijacking when not specifying and managing your own session id. It is\u001b[41;3Hnot the be-all and end-all of session hijacking defense, but it's a good start.\r\u001b[42d; https://php.net/session.use-only-cookies\r\u001b[43dsession.use_only_cookies = 1\r\u001b[44d\u001b[K\u001b[45d; Name of the session (used as cookie name).\r\u001b[46d; https://php.net/session.name\r\u001b[47dsession.name = PHPSESSID\r\u001b[48d\u001b[K\u001b[49d; Initialize session on request startup.\u001b[K\u001b[50;3Hhttps://php.net/session.auto-start\u001b[K\r\u001b[51dsession.auto_start = 0\u001b[K\r\u001b[52d\u001b[K\u001b[53d; Lifetime in seconds of cookie or, if 0, until browser is restarted.\r\u001b[54d; https://php.net/session.cookie-lifetime\r\u001b[55dsession.cookie_lifetime = 0\r\u001b[56d\u001b[K\u001b[57d; The path for which the cookie is valid.\r\u001b[58d; https://php.net/session.cookie-path\r\u001b[59dsession.cookie_path = /\r\u001b[60d\u001b[K\u001b[61d; The domain for which the cookie is valid.\u001b[62;3Hhttps://php.net/session.cookie-domain\r\u001b[63dsession.cookie_domain =\u001b[K\r\u001b[64d\u001b[K\u001b[33d;"]
